  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Parting at the Upper Country
  author: An Jin
  language: eng
  text: |-
    We spread our farewell feast high upon the green stream's shore,
    As the western suburbs darken, dust turns the sky to gold.
    This year the snows and rains stretch through the cold feast days,
    And everywhere the flowers miss their proper season's call.
    The tender grass that springs cannot hold back the departing horse,
    Nor can the willow's green arms bind the traveler to stay.
    A man is born with ambitions that reach toward distant lands—
    Why should we grieve when duty calls us to diverging paths?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'cold feast days' (寒食, hansik) refers to a traditional period of tomb-sweeping and ancestral veneration, typically occurring in early spring, making this a poem of spring parting.
  - key: ''
    value: The contrast between natural beauty (grass, willows, flowers) and human duty reflects a classical theme in East Asian poetry about the necessity of separation despite emotional attachment.
